[1] Queensland (new case), New South Wales
Date: Wed 12 Oct 2011
Source: The Australian [edited]
http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/health-science/hendra-virus-now-endemic-in-two-states/story-e6frg8y6-1226164301417


One horse quarantined and another put down in Queensland/New South
Wales (NSW) outbreak
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The Hendra virus was declared endemic in 2 states yesterday [11 Oct
2011] as it was confirmed that another outbreak had left at least one
horse dead.

In the 18th case across Queensland and NSW this year [2011], a
property in Caboolture, 54 km [33.5 mi] north of Brisbane, was
quarantined yesterday [11 Oct 2011] following confirmation a horse had
the deadly flying fox-borne disease.

The horse was put down yesterday after becoming unsteady and having
difficulty eating over the weekend [8-9 Oct 2011]. Another horse at
the Beachmere property collapsed and died last week with Hendra-type
symptoms and test results are expected today.

Queensland chief veterinary officer Rick Symons said the virus was
already considered endemic in Queensland but this year reported cases
had spread south across the border.

"It is endemic in NSW," he said. "In the past up to this year [2011],
there has only been 1 case in NSW; this year we've seen 8 cases. It
has certainly been a changing picture for NSW."

Dr Symons said 2011 was undoubtedly the more severe year, though the
cause remained undetermined. "This year has been the worst year for
Hendra virus cases," he said. "There is no doubt that 2011 has been a
difficult year for this virus."

Before this year's extraordinary cluster, 14 horses had died since
1994. This year, 22 horses have died in 10 outbreaks in Queensland and
8 in NSW.

Dr Symons warned horse owners and vets to be aware that horses could
contract Hendra at any time throughout the year. The virus is spread
between flying foxes but it is fatal to horses.

Of the 7 people who contracted Hendra virus 4 have died [in years
previous.]

Hendra is more virulent this year. Dr Symons said baseline Hendra
levels were 8-10 per cent in colonies, but this year up to 60 per cent
of flying foxes were excreting Hendra, perhaps because of additional
stresses from the summer flooding.

Queensland's chief health officer, Jeannette Young, said all 66 people
monitored for Hendra this year [2011] had been cleared. 8 people at
the Beachmere property who had "low to negligible" contact declined
testing, a Queensland Health spokeswoman said.

Queensland Horse Council president Debbie Dekker said unusual signs
shown by the horses were a warning for owners to remain vigilant.

"There are instances of Hendra at the moment but there are cases that
have come through that nobody would have ever called a vet before,"
she said.

"We're picking up cases that we never would have before. It's here, it
has always been here. Now that we know about it, we have to start
taking precautions."

30 dogs have also been tested this year; 1 had contracted the virus
and was euthanised. 19 properties were quarantined across Queensland
and 118 horses have been tested.

Yesterday [11 Oct 2011], Queensland Premier Anna Bligh announced AUD 7
million [USD 7.14 million] for research including Hendra virus
transmission, flying fox dispersal, and the effectiveness of a
proposed horse vaccine.

[Byline: Rosanne Barrett]

