[2] Hendra research projects
Date: Wed 12 Oct 2011
Source: ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) [edited]
http://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-10-12/hendra-research-projects-announced/3553744


Hendra research projects announced
----------------------------------
Scientists are hoping to unlock the mysteries of the deadly Hendra
virus, with 5 new research projects announced today [12 Oct 2011].

More than 20 horses have died after catching the disease in Queensland
and New South Wales so far this year [2011].

It is hoped researchers will be able to discover how the virus is
transmitted and how to stop it spreading to horses and, more
importantly, humans.

Work is also continuing on a Hendra vaccine.

The projects are being coordinated through the cross-border Hendra
taskforce, which includes vets, health officers, and scientists.

NSW Department of Primary Industries chief vet Ian Roth says the
future of the virus is a mystery. "We have to work out how it's
transmitted along with looking at other risks, and that will certainly
put us in a better situation into the future," Mr Roth said.

NSW Primary Industries Minister Katrina Hodgkinson says 2011 has been
the most fatal year for the disease the 2 states have seen. "In NSW
the virus claimed 10 horse deaths at 8 properties, all on the NSW
north coast," Ms Hodgkinson said.

"These critical new research projects aim to get to the bottom of this
year's spike and look at new ways to reduce further cases in the
future and ultimately minimise the risk of human infection."

There have also been 12 cases in Queensland, with a horse put down
yesterday [11 Oct 2011] in the latest case on a property at Beachmere,
north of Brisbane.

Among the new research projects announced, the world-renowned
Elizabeth Macarthur Agricultural Institute will lead an AUD 900 000
[USD 917 000] study looking at virology issues, including new
state-of-the-art testing techniques.

An epidemiologist from the Wollongbar Primary Industries Institute is
also undertaking one of the research projects, examining the
transmission of the virus from flying foxes to horses and the impact
flying fox dispersal has on virus infection levels.

The New South Wales and Queensland Governments have committed a total
of AUD 6 million [USD 6.11 million] to the projects, and the Federal
Government has matched their commitment.

Submissions are now being sought for the remaining funds

[Byline: Nastasia Campanella]

